Marketing Brief -- News Corp.:
   Media Firm Plans to Raise
   $300 Million in Note Issue
The notes filed for yesterday will be due 2002 and will
have a value of $619 million in principal at maturity. The
notes can be exchanged any time for ordinary shares or
American depositary shares (each representing two ordinary
shares) of News Corp. The notes are guaranteed on a
subordinated basis by News Corp.
   News Corp. said that in 1997, note-holders may require the
company to purchase their notes, and the company may elect to
pay them in cash, ADRs or a combination of both. The filing
was made by News Corp., based in Sydney, Australia, and its
U.S. unit, News America Holdings Inc., and includes an
application to list the notes on the New York Stock Exchange.